snippet.description:
Ana Luz Porzecanski answers kids' questions about Cuba in this video interview. She's a conservation biologist at the American Museum of Natural History.

What is Cuba?
What kinds of environments exist in Cuba? 
What is biodiversity? Why is it so important, anyway?
Why is the biodiversity of Cuba so important?
What plants or animals live only in Cuba?
How does the biodiversity of Cuba differ from biodiversity around the world?
How are animals in Cuba different than those in the U.S.? 
Can I see any of Cuba's animals at the zoo? Can I have one as a pet?
Are there any invasive species in Cuba?
How might Cuba's biodiversity change in the future?

Find more videos, games and activities in Ology, a science website 
for kids from  the American Museum  of Natural History.

snippet.description:
Ana Luz Porzecanski responde a las preguntas de los niños sobre Cuba en esta video entrevista. Ana es bióloga de conservación en el Museo Americano de Historia Natural en Nueva York.

En este vídeo, Ana responde a las siguientes preguntas:
¿Qué es Cuba?
¿Qué tipo de ambientes y paisajes naturales hay en Cuba?
¿Qué es biodiversidad? ¿Y por qué es tan importante?
¿Por qué es tan importante la biodiversidad de Cuba?
¿Qué plantas y animales viven sólo en Cuba?
¿En qué se diferencia la biodiversidad Cubana a la de otros sitios del mundo?
¿En qué se diferencian los animales Cubanos de los animales de Estados Unidos?
¿Puedo ver algún animal cubano en el zoológico? 
¿Puedo tener uno de mascota?"
¿Hay especies invasoras en Cuba?
En el futuro ¿Cómo puede cambiar la biodiversidad de Cuba?

Puedes encontrar más vídeos, juegos y actividades en Ology, la web para niños del American Museum of Natural History.

snippet.description:
Susan Perkins answers kids' questions about microbes! She is a microbiologist at the American Museum of Natural History. Susan is also the curator of The Secret World Inside You. It's an exhibition about the human microbiome, the trillions of microbes that live in and on us.

In this video Susan answers the following questions:
What are microbes?
What do microbes look like?
Where do microbes live?
Are microbes good or bad?
Are viruses microbes?
How many microbes are in a body? How many on earth?
Do cats and dogs have the same microbes than people?
Why do you have microbes in your stomach? What do they do?
What kind of scientists studies microbes?
How long have microbes been on earth?

Find more videos, games and activities in Ology, a science website 
for kids from  the American Museum  of Natural History.
